When a probation officer believes a violation has occurred, they may file a report and request a hearing. You might receive a notice in the mail with a court date, or you could be arrested and brought directly to court. At the probation violation hearing, the judge can:

• Find no violation and continue your existing probation;
• Find a violation but give you another chance with the same or modified conditions;
• Order you to serve some or all of the jail or prison time that was previously stayed.

Because judges have significant discretion, the way your violation is presented—and how your progress, challenges, and support system are explained—can make a major difference.

The best strategy in a probation case often starts before you ever step in front of the judge. Andrew works to:

• Review the original sentence and all probation conditions;
• Analyze the probation officer’s report and any alleged violations;
• Identify whether the violation can be contested on the facts or law;
• Present context and mitigation—such as health issues, transportation problems, or steps you’ve already taken to get back on track;
• Negotiate with probation and the prosecutor for alternatives to jail, like treatment, community-based sanctions, or a structured plan to finish your conditions.

The goal is to convince the court that you are still a good candidate for probation and that revoking your freedom is not necessary.

Interference with a 911 call is usually charged as a gross misdemeanor. That means you may face:

• Up to 1 year in jail;
• Fines up to $3,000;
• Probation, treatment, or counseling requirements;
• No-contact orders that remove you from your home or family;
• A permanent criminal record that can affect employment, housing, and future background checks.

When this charge is filed alongside domestic assault or other offenses, the total stakes can be even higher, including potential firearm restrictions and long-term consequences for your rights and reputation.

These cases often involve detailed and complex evidence. Law enforcement may use crash reconstruction, event data recorders (“black box” data), vehicle inspections, toxicology reports, and witness statements to build their case. Prosecutors frequently allege:

• Driving while impaired by alcohol or drugs;
• Grossly negligent or reckless driving behavior;
• Excessive speeding, racing, or passing in dangerous conditions;
• Texting or other distracted driving;
• Leaving the scene of a crash involving injury or death.

Our job is to carefully review every piece of evidence, identify weaknesses or inconsistencies, and make sure that the state is held to its burden of proof.

In many cases, a criminal vehicular homicide charge is tied to an allegation of driving while impaired. That means the strength of the state’s case may depend on:

• How the traffic stop occurred and whether it was lawful;
• Whether field sobriety tests were properly administered;
• Whether breath or blood tests were taken according to procedure;
• The timing of any testing and the handling of samples.

Challenging the underlying DWI evidence can be a crucial part of defending against criminal vehicular homicide. If the state’s proof of impairment is weak or unreliable, it may significantly impact how the case is charged and resolved.

Criminal vehicular homicide is a serious felony offense. A conviction can result in:

• A lengthy prison sentence;
• Substantial fines and restitution claims;
• Long-term or permanent loss of driving privileges;
• Felony probation with strict conditions;
• A permanent criminal record that affects employment and housing;
• Emotional and family consequences that can last for years.

Because the stakes are so high, it is critical to have a lawyer who understands both the legal and human sides of these cases.

These cases are emotionally charged for everyone involved—families, survivors, and the accused. At Davis Defense, we believe it is possible to respect the seriousness of the loss while still insisting on a fair process and a strong defense. We will:

• Listen to your story and explain your options in clear, honest terms;
• Conduct a thorough, independent review of the evidence;
• Work with experts when appropriate, such as accident reconstructionists or toxicologists;
• Explore all possible resolutions, including reduced charges or alternative outcomes, when available;
• Be prepared to take your case to trial if that is in your best interest.
